creasing in all age groups. mostly came, more came between the ages of sixty and sixty nine. They were seventeen percent, fifty to fifty-nine thirteen, and forty to forty-nine twelve percent. The positive point is that last week the number of people aged ninety and over fell by a quarter. We know that the Covid disease progresses both with and without symptoms, but last week the percentage of patients without symptoms was ten percent. And one hundred and eighty-seven people required hospitalization. It is very important that nearly eighty percent of those hospitalized were over the age of sixty, which also indicates that the disease will worsen and the course of the disease will be more serious in older people. We continue to be concerned about care facilities, which continue to be the most vulnerable risk areas, and we did a small analysis that when we compared the fourteen-day morbidity per hundred thousand inhabitants, both in nursing homes and among the general population, among the sixty plus clients staying in nursing homes, the risk of infection is almost seven times higher. That again, when the disease gets into nursing homes, it's a serious problem. And, of course, we keep repeating that our healthcare system is currently under a very heavy load. And we have to do everything to ensure that all people who need hospital treatment, not only those with Covid, but also people who come to the hospital with other problems, get this treatment. A few words about Harjumaa's illness. As of today, the fourteen-day morbidity rate per one hundred thousand inhabitants was five hundred and fifty-eight point eighty-two. The number in Tallinn was five hundred and ninety, in the city of Loksa one thousand three hundred and thirty-eight, in the city of Maardu seven hundred and fifty-one. But let's compare it again with Ida-Virumaa, where this indicator is one thousand and fifty-three, that Ida-Virumaa is still the biggest worry for us right now. In Harju County, there are almost seventeen thousand people under active monitoring, fourteen thousand of them are close contacts and over three thousand are active disease cases, and today we have twenty-four active cases, which are mostly work, workplaces, family cases, but there are also nursing homes. And now, what should we do next, how should we behave? Figuratively speaking, for us to overcome this crisis, everything is very, very simple and clear. Everyone who is sick must suffer through the disease peacefully at home, and during the time when they are contagious, all sick people should keep their contact to a minimum. So that we can get rid of the virus. Well, that's the kind of ideal world we're moving towards. But it is certainly not possible for us to achieve this 100 percent. But still, we all have to work together now to not spread the virus and help those who need help. And what do we continue to do, we adhere to the measures established in the country, keep our distance, wear a mask, reduce contacts, avoid, avoid crowded places and events, this time we will cancel big parties. And we celebrate Christmas mostly at home and in a narrow family circle and with the people we communicate with on a daily basis and we stay at home as much as possible and enjoy the beautiful Estonian nature in order to reduce the risk of getting infected ourselves and not passing the infection on to anyone in the family circle. I wish everyone a nice Christmas and stay healthy, thank you! Thank you, Dr. Irina Donchenko and the corona virus in the view of Tallinn Mayor Mihhail Kõlvart. Hello from me too, based on the epidemiological situation, from this week, high school students will continue to do distance learning, and elementary school students will continue to do so, but the content of the study is primarily creative tasks and also this kind of creative learning. As announced at the end of last week, Tallinn municipal schools also offer elementary school students the opportunity to receive the long-day