onal, it is undoubtedly a great responsibility and challenge to manage the communication of such a large group. A total of nearly twenty thousand people work here. The activities of this group affect the daily lives of hundreds of thousands of people. There are major reorganizations taking place in Tallinn, the management of Tallinn is currently taking place, and communication has its role, how will these changes really work. In Tallinn communications or city media, these reorganizations began already in the autumn of 2019. And we continue to work hard to ensure that important news in the city reaches everyone. I thank you for this trust and I try to work as well as I can. Thank you! Thank you, Kirsti Ruul, the city's communications director since January 1, two thousand and twenty-one. Christmas and the end of the year are fast approaching, then there are fireworks at the end of the year and other suitable things. And today we have words of admonition from both the mayor and the representative of the Animal Protection Society. Mayor Mihhail Kõlvart. Yes, fireworks are traditionally one of the symbols of New Year's Eve. The city has also organized it every year, and this year perhaps this event has a special meaning. Well, first of all, we all need positive emotions, which we don't have very much lately. And the city has tried to offer this emotion in the urban space. At the same time, we have to take into account the current epidemiological situation. So, of course, such a traditional event will not take place on Freedom Square. And we want to distract people. So this year fireworks will be held in different places, in different districts, almost in every district, except for Nõmme and Kristiine. Today, six places have been chosen where the fireworks will take place. And we once again appeal to the townspeople that if we want these events to take place, for the fireworks organized by the city to take place, then it is necessary to keep a distance and also wear a mask. At the same time, the places have been chosen in such a way that this possibility exists. But we have another very important appeal to the people of Tallinn. That we organize fireworks centrally in different places, hoping that people will organize it privately, will not buy, and will not shoot. Because it is a problem for both humans and animals. And it's an annual problem, and we have to understand that it's not environmentally friendly either. And we really hope that this understanding will arise among our people in general this year. That there are specialists who can do it professionally, and that's why we do it, but all private fireworks should be stopped, that we try to protect each other, as well as our smaller friends, and I would gladly pass the word on to the representative of the Animal Protection Society. Thank you, Mr. Mayor. Yes, Kaisa Kamm, head of direct assistance of the Estonian Animal Protection Society, will participate in the press conference, so the happy New Year's Eve is a bit worrying for you. Please. Hello from the Estonian Animal Protection Society. And first of all, I am very happy that as the year goes on, the more people talk about the negative impact of fireworks on both animals and the environment. At this point, a big thank you to Tallinn, who is now organizing such fireworks organized in a safe environment, and I hope that it will not remain a one-year endeavor and that other cities and municipalities will take an example from it. That the reason why the Estonian Animal Protection Society is so concerned about these fireworks is like several. That, first of all, they are not only the concern of our pets, dogs and cats, but also of general urban animals, including horses and birds. But I think I would first like to talk about the animals in our home. Fireworks are very frustrating for them because they are loud and cause irrational fear in dogs. That they don't know how to behave, they start to run away, they freeze, that I believe that if someone manages to study the statistics of the animal shelter in Tallinn, that there are very, very many of these running dogs, that it can cause accidents. Plus just a worry. In addition to that, there are also our birds who are in the city. They either fly very far, they never make it back, food supplies run out. That we are simply causing them a lot of suffering for no reason at all. So that's why it would be great if you just go to places that are controlled, we know where they're happening. Pet owners can monitor where these fireworks are taking place, and we don't have to fear that if they go outside with their dog, fireworks will be set off indiscriminately. This is one of our main concerns. Thank you! And probably from here we can still supplement and ask that, if at all possible, parents also keep an eye on their babies and that they don't necessarily have to set off their own, self-initiated fireworks on Christmas Eve and the first holiday of Christmas. So maybe we could somehow get rid of this habit. But here you probably need parental care and teaching what is suitable for something and what is not. But thank you in any case, Kaisa Kamm, head of direct assistance at the Estonian Animal Protection Society. Dear journalists, do you have any questions for the participants of our press conference? I can't see the questions, but Mr. Mayor, today, as planned, we have our last meeting of the year here in the press conference hall. We never rule out that an unscheduled post-session press conference or other gathering may be necessary. But according to plan, we will be here today for the last time, because this year, because next week, the city government will hold a session in the city hall. Probably, we hope that the corona situation will allow it. Yes, thank you, indeed, the beautiful season of Christmas and New Year is approaching. There is also the traditional desire to look back, draw conclusions and share plans for the next year. But what I wan